// examples/generic_map.sigil
//
// Plan B Task 51: first user-authored generic syntax to flow through
// the full Sigil pipeline (lex â†’ parse â†’ resolve â†’ typecheck â†’
// elaborate â†’ monomorphize â†’ color â†’ codegen). PR #16 (Task 49)
// pinned the canonical `$$`-mangling format via synthetic-program
// unit tests in `compiler/src/monomorphize.rs`; this example is
// where that format first survives end-to-end through Cranelift on
// real source. The `--reproducibility` check in CI then verifies
// compile-twice byte equality against this binary.
//
// Sigil v1's surface syntax does not include `TypeExpr::Fn`
// (function types are not first-class in parameter / return
// positions; see `examples/higher_order.sigil` for the inline-IIFE
// workaround). The design doc's canonical `map[A, B, e](xs: List[A],
// f: (A) -> B !e) -> List[B] !e` therefore cannot be expressed
// here. The closest Plan B's surface admits is a structure-
// preserving traversal â€” semantically `map id` â€” together with a
// generic `length` fold. That pair is enough to exercise:
//
//   - Generic type cloning: `type List[A]` produces `List$$Int` and
//     `List$$String` per Task 49 monomorphization. The recursive
//     self-reference `Cons(A, List[A])` dedups via `type_seen` so
//     each instantiation produces exactly one clone.
//   - Mangled ctor sites: `Nil$$Int`, `Cons$$Int`, `Nil$$String`,
//     `Cons$$String` allocated through the generic ctor sites
//     in `map`'s and `length`'s match arms and in `main`'s list
//     literals.
//   - Generic fn cloning: `map$$Int` / `map$$String` and
//     `length$$Int` / `length$$String`, four monomorph clones from
//     two declared generic fns.
//   - Pattern matching on generic ctors: scrutinee `Ty::User(_,
//     args)` propagates into per-sub-pattern field types so the
//     inner `Cons(h, t)` correctly types `h: A`, `t: List[A]`
//     against the scrutinee's instantiated `A` (closes the
//     reviewer-flagged regression that landed Task 49 round 3).
//   - Color inference (Task 50): every fn here has row `![]` and
//     transitively calls only Native peers, so all four monomorphs
//     plus `main` (which has `![IO]`) classify as Native â€” the
//     program contains no `perform` to a user-handled effect, only
//     the IO shortcut. Verifiable via `sigil generic_map.sigil
//     --dump-color`.
//   - Final codegen acceptance: post-monomorphization names contain
//     `$` separators. The lexer rejects `$` in surface syntax so
//     these names cannot collide with user identifiers; codegen
//     consumes them as opaque strings into Cranelift's symbol
//     table.
//
// Invariant: writes exactly "3\n2\n" to stdout and exits 0.
//   length(map(Cons(10, Cons(20, Cons(30, Nil)))))    = 3
//   length(map(Cons("a", Cons("b", Nil))))            = 2

import std.int
import std.io
use std.int.{int_to_string};
use std.io.{IO};

type List[A] = | Nil | Cons(A, List[A])

fn map[A](xs: List[A]) -> List[A] ![] {
  match xs {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, map(t)),
  }
}

fn length[A](xs: List[A]) -> Int ![] {
  match xs {
    Nil => 0,
    Cons(_, t) => 1 + length(t),
  }
}

fn main() -> Int ![IO] {
  let ints: List[Int] = Cons(10, Cons(20, Cons(30, Nil)));
  let strs: List[String] = Cons("a", Cons("b", Nil));
  let mapped_ints: List[Int] = map(ints);
  let mapped_strs: List[String] = map(strs);
  perform IO.println(int_to_string(length(mapped_ints)));
  perform IO.println(int_to_string(length(mapped_strs)));
  0
}
